Prior to the late 1960s, the Tamakushi River flowed further north, passing through Higashi-Osaka's Hanazono, Hishiyahigashi, Aramoto, and Shichikenya areas, eventually merging with the {{ill|Kusunone River|ja|楠根川}} near Suwa in {{ill|Jōtō-ku, Osaka|ja|城東区}}. In 1969 (Shōwa 44), the construction of the Second Neyagawa cut off this northern section, with most of it now filled in.
== Environmental restoration == During Japan's {{ill|High Economic Growth Period|ja|高度経済成長}}, the water quality of the Tamakushi River deteriorated due to pollution from upstream sources, including the Nagase and Yamatogawa rivers. Environmental improvements included the creation of walking paths, planting of aquatic vegetation, and installation of simple aeration devices. Juvenile carp and crucian carp were also released into the river during this time.
== Scenic features == The area south of Kashiwamura in Yao City consists of expansive fields, while the surroundings of {{ill|Kawachi-Yamamoto Station|ja|河内山本駅}} on the {{ill|Kintetsu Osaka Line|ja|近鉄大阪線}} are commercial zones. The rest of the area is primarily quiet residential neighborhoods. Cherry trees were planted along the riverbanks in sections such as Futamata, Kashiwamura Bridge to Gogatsubashi intersection, and Yamamoto Bridge to Yamamoto-cho Kita 7-chome. These trees, planted starting in January 1965 through community efforts and donations, bloom annually from late March to early April.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|author=Yao City Charm Book Committee|title=Wao!Yao! Entrance to Yao|publisher=140B|date=2013-03-27}}</ref> This cherry blossom row was selected for the {{ill|100 Green Spots of Osaka|ja|大阪みどりの百選}}.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite web|ja|url=https://www.pref.osaka.lg.jp/attach/25974/00195639/hyakusenn.pdf|title=「大阪みどりの百選」|publisher=Osaka Prefecture|accessdate=2018-03-29}}</ref>
