{{Infobox 河川 |名称= Tamakushi River (玉串川) |image= [[File:Tamakusi-river01.JPG|300px]] |image説明= Near Yamamoto Stadium in Yao City, Yamamoto-cho Minami 7-chome, September 18, 2006 |水系等級= {{ill|Class 1 Water System|ja|一級水系|qq=draft|qq=draft}} |水系= {{ill|Yodo River|ja|淀川|qq=draft|qq=draft}} |種別= {{ill|Class 1 River (Japan)|ja|一級河川|qq=draft|qq=draft}} |延長= Approximately 6.4 km |標高= -- |流量= -- |観測所= |流域面積= -- |水源= {{ill|Nagase River (Osaka)|ja|長瀬川 (大阪府)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}<small> ({{ill|Yao, Osaka|ja|八尾市|qq=draft|qq=draft}} Futamata)</small> |河口= <small>{{ill|Second Neyagawa|ja|第二寝屋川|qq=draft|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Higashi-Osaka|ja|東大阪市|qq=draft|qq=draft}} Tamakushi Motomachi)</small> |流域= {{ill|Osaka Prefecture|ja|大阪府|qq=draft|qq=draft}} |脚注= |出典= }}
'''Tamakushi River''' (玉串川) is an {{ill|Agricultural drainage canal|ja|農業用排水路|qq=draft|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Statutory public property|ja|法定外公共物|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) flowing through {{ill|Osaka Prefecture|ja|大阪府|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Together with the {{ill|Nagase River (Osaka)|ja|長瀬川 (大阪府)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, it has been selected by the Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries as one of the {{ill|100 Famous Irrigation Systems|ja|疎水百選|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref>{{Cite web|ja|title=八尾市内の主な河川・水路|url=https://www.city.yao.osaka.jp/0000061083.html|publisher=八尾市都市整備部土木管財課|date=2021-12-09|accessdate=2022-11-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|ja|title=大阪府／大和川分水築留掛かり|url=https://www.pref.osaka.lg.jp/chubunm/chubu_nm/tukidome.html|publisher=大阪府|date=2020-10-09|accessdate=2022-11-17}}</ref>
== Geography == The Tamakushi River branches from the {{ill|Nagase River (Osaka)|ja|長瀬川 (大阪府)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} at Futamata in {{ill|Yao, Osaka|ja|八尾市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, flows north through the center of Yao City, and joins the {{ill|Second Neyagawa|ja|第二寝屋川|qq=draft|qq=draft}} at {{ill|Higashi-Osaka|ja|東大阪市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Tamakushi Motomachi. The river is approximately 5 meters wide, with stone or block embankments on both sides.
== Municipalities along the river == ; {{ill|Osaka Prefecture|ja|大阪府|qq=draft|qq=draft}} : {{ill|Yao, Osaka|ja|八尾市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Higashi-Osaka|ja|東大阪市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
== History == The river's name, "Tamakushi," is thought to originate from an event in the 6th year of Tenpyō Shōhō (754 CE), when a sacred offering, Tamakushige, was floated down from the upper Yamatogawa to calm storms. The offering reached a pond in Tsubara (now Hanazono Hommachi), leading to the establishment of {{ill|Tsubara Shrine|ja|津原神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} to enshrine the deity. It is said that the region subsequently experienced no further storm damage.
During the Edo period, the river divided at the southernmost tip of {{ill|Kawachi Province|ja|河内国|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Wakae District|ja|若江郡|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (now Yao City, Futamata), into the {{ill|Kyūhōji River|ja|久宝寺川|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and the {{ill|Tamakushi River|ja|玉串川|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
The {{ill|Yamatogawa Diversion Project|ja|大和川付替え|qq=draft|qq=draft}} of 1704 (Hōei 1) caused farmland along the old riverbed to lose its water source. The former riverbed was later repurposed for irrigation, resulting in the current Nagase and Tamakushi rivers. Details of post-diversion history can be found under Nagase River.
Prior to the late 1960s, the Tamakushi River flowed further north, passing through Higashi-Osaka's Hanazono, Hishiyahigashi, Aramoto, and Shichikenya areas, eventually merging with the {{ill|Kusunone River|ja|楠根川|qq=draft|qq=draft}} near Suwa in {{ill|Jōtō-ku, Osaka|ja|城東区|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. In 1969 (Shōwa 44), the construction of the Second Neyagawa cut off this northern section, with most of it now filled in.
== Environmental restoration == During Japan's {{ill|High Economic Growth Period|ja|高度経済成長|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the water quality of the Tamakushi River deteriorated due to pollution from upstream sources, including the Nagase and Yamatogawa rivers. Environmental improvements included the creation of walking paths, planting of aquatic vegetation, and installation of simple aeration devices. Juvenile carp and crucian carp were also released into the river during this time.
== Scenic features == The area south of Kashiwamura in Yao City consists of expansive fields, while the surroundings of {{ill|Kawachi-Yamamoto Station|ja|河内山本駅|qq=draft|qq=draft}} on the {{ill|Kintetsu Osaka Line|ja|近鉄大阪線|qq=draft|qq=draft}} are commercial zones. The rest of the area is primarily quiet residential neighborhoods. Cherry trees were planted along the riverbanks in sections such as Futamata, Kashiwamura Bridge to Gogatsubashi intersection, and Yamamoto Bridge to Yamamoto-cho Kita 7-chome. These trees, planted starting in January 1965 through community efforts and donations, bloom annually from late March to early April.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|author=Yao City Charm Book Committee|title=Wao!Yao! Entrance to Yao|publisher=140B|date=2013-03-27}}</ref> This cherry blossom row was selected for the {{ill|100 Green Spots of Osaka|ja|大阪みどりの百選|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite web|ja|url=https://www.pref.osaka.lg.jp/attach/25974/00195639/hyakusenn.pdf|title=「大阪みどりの百選」|publisher=Osaka Prefecture|accessdate=2018-03-29}}</ref>
=== Facilities along the river === * {{ill|Akemigawa Elementary School|ja|八尾市立曙川東小学校|qq=draft|qq=draft}} * Tsurumishima Shrine * {{ill|Oji Station (Kintetsu Osaka Line)|ja|近鉄大阪線 恩智駅|qq=draft|qq=draft}} * {{ill|Osaka Prefectural Road 15|ja|大阪府道15号八尾茨木線|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (runs parallel to the river near Oji Station) * {{ill|National Route 170|ja|国道170号|qq=draft|qq=draft}} Osaka Outer Loop Line * Kashiwamura Inari Shrine * {{ill|Osaka Prefectural Road 182|ja|大阪府道182号柏村南本町線|qq=draft|qq=draft}} Kashiwamura Bridge Intersection * Kongo Yao Junior and Senior High School * Genki Onsen Yao Oyu-ba (Kashiwajyu Onsen) * Seiyu Kindergarten * Osaka Gas Dormitory * {{ill|Takaoka High School|ja|大阪府立山本高等学校|qq=draft|qq=draft}} * Takaoka Sakura Shopping Street * {{ill|Yamamoto Baseball Stadium|ja|八尾市立山本球場|qq=draft|qq=draft}} * {{ill|Kintetsu Osaka Line|ja|近鉄大阪線|qq=draft|qq=draft}} Kawachi-Yamamoto Station
